Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:=20
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday! Welcome to our 6th Weekly Dose of Optimism, where we celebrat=
e the incredible accomplishments humans manage to pull off and the progress=
 that we=E2=80=99re =E2=80=94 unsteadily and windingly =E2=80=94 making.
It=E2=80=99s been awesome to see the positive response to the Weekly Dose s=
o far. If you=E2=80=99re enjoying it, spread the optimism by forwarding thi=
s email or sharing the newsletter on social.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by my daily dose=E2=80=A6 Athletic Greens=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/0a0b6b08-f9a8-4bc8-98b8-07fa81a2ff1d?r=3D9=
p0gt ]
It=E2=80=99s easier to be optimistic when you start your day right. Every m=
orning, I drink a homemade concoction starring Athletic Greens=E2=80=99 AG1=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/24effb58-a27b-4396-b50a-a5bb1cd24196?r=3D9=
p0gt ]. It=E2=80=99s one of the few products I actually use daily.
An AG1 subscription isn=E2=80=99t cheap =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s ~$79/month o=
r almost $1,000 year. But if being at the top of your game is as important =
to you as it is to me, it=E2=80=99s worth it.
Not Boring optimists can get a free one-year supply of Vitamin D and 5 trav=
el packs when you order with the special Not Boring link [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/24effb58-a27b-4396-b50a-a5bb1cd24196?r=3D9p0gt ].
(1) US regulators will certify first small nuclear reactor design [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/c30de121-b60e-4fe6-9b04-d232458eb43c?r=3D9p0gt ]
John Timmer [ https://substack.com/redirect/659dd364-e2e6-4e91-8012-8260156=
87e5d?r=3D9p0gt ] for Ars Technica
Small modular reactors have been promoted as avoiding many of the problems =
that have made large nuclear plants exceedingly expensive to build. They're=
 small enough that they can be assembled on a factory floor and then shippe=
d to the site where they will operate, eliminating many of the challenges o=
f custom on-site construction.
After six years of waiting, NuScale received design certification from the =
Nuclear Regulatory Commission for its small modular reactor. While deployme=
nt is likely years away, design certification is another positive step towa=
rds a more affordable, scalable nuclear-powered future.
Elsewhere, on Tuesday, German Chancellor Olaf Scholz said for the first tim=
e that it =E2=80=9Ccould make sense=E2=80=9D to keep Germany=E2=80=99s last=
 three nuclear reactors online. [ https://substack.com/redirect/b08392a2-2d=
e8-4d66-9700-1a72b3b383b9?r=3D9p0gt ] While nuclear only generates 6% of Ge=
rmany=E2=80=99s energy today, this is a notable shift in the EU=E2=80=99s m=
ost populous country=E2=80=99s posture towards nuclear.
(2) The U.S. Is Investing Big in Chips. So Is the Rest of the World. [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/5a1eddb4-82be-4059-bb5a-285b9ad98639?r=3D9p0gt ]
Jiyoung Sohn [ https://substack.com/redirect/56b93a22-bb33-498b-abac-661e21=
8ce8b3?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Wall Street Journal
The new U.S. incentives, which cleared Congress after a House vote on Thurs=
day, will help reduce the significantly higher price tag of placing an adva=
nced chip factory on American soil.
The semiconductor industry is already flush with investment and incentives =
from private companies, capital markets, and governments. The question is n=
ot whether semiconductor companies have the capital they need to continue t=
o produce & innovate on chips, but whether CHIPs Act subsidies can convince=
 them to do so in the U.S.
This pairs nicely with Noah Smith=E2=80=99s [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/7fbe434d-9349-429b-9b7b-3eaf7785fed0?r=3D9p0gt ] Industrial policy starts =
with semiconductors [ https://substack.com/redirect/0c2472f0-b2a1-42f0-b9d8=
-2cd153071b84?r=3D9p0gt ]. Smith explains why industrial policy starts with=
 semiconductors, the U.S. current (and future) standing in the semiconducto=
r industry, and why it=E2=80=99s crucial that startups get CHIPs funding.
(3) The brain that defied Alzheimer=E2=80=99s [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/b10b6f12-e4ee-495d-8951-d9829aefbed7?r=3D9p0gt ]
Neil Osterweil for The Harvard Gazette
This patient gave us a window into many competing forces =E2=80=94 abnormal=
 protein accumulation, inflammation, lipid metabolism, homeostatic mechanis=
ms =E2=80=94 that either promote or protect against disease progression.
A couple of weeks ago, Science published a piece titled Blots on a Field [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/1d69a29a-e209-4e61-a09f-e3b96e22469c?r=3D9p0g=
t ] in which they reported that a study published in 2006 which has underpi=
nned the =E2=80=9Camyloid hypothesis of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s, which holds th=
at A=CE=B2 clumps, known as plaques, in brain tissue are a primary cause of=
 the devastating illness=E2=80=9D was based on fabricated images. It was de=
vastating news for Alzheimer=E2=80=99s research, as the study led researche=
rs on a 16 year, multi-billion dollar wild goose chase for naught.=20
Chalk this one up under =E2=80=9COptimism isn=E2=80=99t a belief that every=
thing will go well all the time. It=E2=80=99s a belief that despite the ine=
vitable challenges, we will make progress.=E2=80=9D
This week, The Harvard Gazette covered the 2019 Massachusetts General Hospi=
tal discovery of a gene mutation that might improve resistance to Alzheimer=
=E2=80=99s, and work that=E2=80=99s being done to develop therapies based o=
n the discovery.=20
In New Zealand, researchers at The University of Otago published a study [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/b947eb77-39e6-4042-b3ee-cfb18cae7654?r=3D9p0g=
t ] in Frontiers in Neuroscience that =E2=80=9Cfound a particular brain pro=
tein changed the gene expression and protein profile of the human neuron in=
 pathways linked to enhancing learning and memory,=E2=80=9D and are working=
 to figure out how the protein or its derivatives might be delivered to the=
 brain and be used as a therapy.=20
Both are early, but it=E2=80=99s cool to see that in the face of one huge s=
etback, the human colossus is hard at work finding alternative routes.=20
(4) New hardware offers faster computation for artificial intelligence, wit=
h much less energy [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ced2914-b2e2-4a8c-976d-=
d8bfee88174b?r=3D9p0gt ]
Adam Zewe [ https://substack.com/redirect/d04fec59-cbef-40f1-8aa0-7db2801ea=
7b2?r=3D9p0gt ] for MIT News Office
These programmable resistors vastly increase the speed at which a neural ne=
twork is trained, while drastically reducing the cost and energy to perform=
 that training. This could help scientists develop deep learning models muc=
h more quickly, which could then be applied in uses like self-driving cars,=
 fraud detection, or medical image analysis.
A MIT team of 1,000,000x engineers has developed a =E2=80=9Chuman-made anal=
og synapse=E2=80=9D that operates 1 million times faster than previous vers=
ions (which also happens to be 1 million times faster than the human brain.=
) 10x engineers are very 2019. What this means in practice: it=E2=80=99s be=
coming increasingly faster, efficient, and cheaper to train complex neural =
networks. Breakthroughs in processing power enable the innovations that wil=
l shape our daily lives =E2=80=94 autonomous driving, medical image analysi=
s, brain-computer interfaces, and much more.
(5) Pig organs partially revived in dead animals =E2=80=94 researchers are =
stunned [ https://substack.com/redirect/2dcf040b-f113-4b61-bde6-e1bdf11512a=
b?r=3D9p0gt ]
Max Kozlov [ https://substack.com/redirect/26bc9780-75e6-4104-a0a8-5fad2a4d=
63c4?r=3D9p0gt ] for Nature
Researchers connected pigs that had been dead for one hour to a system call=
ed OrganEx that pumped a blood substitute throughout the animals=E2=80=99 b=
odies. The solution =E2=80=94 containing the animals=E2=80=99 blood and 13 =
compounds such as anticoagulants =E2=80=94 slowed the decomposition of the =
bodies and quickly restored some organ function, such as heart contraction =
and activity in the liver and kidney.
The results of the experiment, led by Yale neuroscientist Nenad Sestan, rai=
se questions about our definition of death. While researchers were unable t=
o fully re-animate the =E2=80=9Cdead=E2=80=9D pigs, they restored circulati=
on and cellular activity in vital organs. We are still years away from touc=
hing humans with anything like this, but the results challenge the previous=
 conception that cardiac death is irreversible.=20
Zvonimir Vrselja, a researcher on the team, noted, =E2=80=9CWe made cells d=
o something they weren=E2=80=99t able to do=E2=80=A6We=E2=80=99re not sayin=
g it=E2=80=99s clinically relevant, but it=E2=80=99s moving in the right di=
rection.=E2=80=9D Or in web3-speak: =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re still so early!=
=E2=80=9D
Bonus: The Case for Longtermism [ https://substack.com/redirect/dcd4dfbc-f7=
a0-49bc-b953-fc6e5053d510?r=3D9p0gt ]
William MacAskill [ https://substack.com/redirect/7ef7bbf2-00fc-4b75-bece-c=
2c3ea4c1dca?r=3D9p0gt ] for The New York Times
Longtermism is about taking seriously just how big the future could be and =
how high the stakes are in shaping it. If humanity survives to even a fract=
ion of its potential life span, then, strange as it may seem, we are the an=
cients: we live at the very beginning of history, in its most distant past.=
 What we do now will affect untold numbers of future people. We need to act=
 wisely.
Will MacAskill, one of the originators of effective altruism, makes the cas=
e for longtermism. The argument goes that, on the grand scale of history, w=
e humans today are just the beginning of the story and we have a key moral =
imperative today to live in a way that positively impacts the long-term fut=
ure. Another one of those mind bending reminders of just how small each of =
us is, yet how important our actions can be.
